  "active_lock_reason": null,
  "body": "The tests for ERC-20 token contracts does not cover all the behavior described by the actual standard. Some issues are already described in #616, but there are more. For example:\r\n\r\n* Testing the return values of certain functions.\r\n* Testing the triggered events.\r\n\r\nTesting all the defined behavior requires lots of tests. In addition I believe having ERC-20 token thoroughly and pessimistically tested is in place. This includes testing functions with different marginal inputs and their combination (like mentioned 0x0 addresses, 0 values and like) even this leads to test duplication.\r\n\r\nI tried to find ERC-20 testing library (and also [asked](https://ethereum.stackexchange.com/questions/31166/is-there-erc20-token-test-library)). Like package with tests written to test ERC-20 compliance. Since it is a standard with defined behavior those compliance tests can be written generally for any implementation. Yet I have found nothing.\r\n\r\nThus I [started such a package](https://github.com/CryptoverseRocks/token-test-suite). It's aim is to test compliance with the ERC-20 token standard. Reusable tests. Even when one's token smart contract is based on some well-tested library it is beneficial to recheck. Especially when overriding functions to ensure nothing got broken.\r\n\r\nBut I think `zeppelin-solidity` can also benefit from it. It is easy to integrate and I have already prepared a branch [mancze:test/erc20-testing](/mancze/zeppelin-solidity/tree/test/erc20) for it (its a draft, not PR). Check and see. Run with:\r\n\r\n```\r\nnpm test ./test/StandardToken.erc20.test.js\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe token test suite still needs improvements and has some gaps. But if it makes sense it can be completed. Integrating with `zeppelin-solidity` would fix #616 and provide the missing tests for ERC-20 standard compliance.",
